failures.title: Camshaft Fault
failures.description: Camshaft failure on a Kenworth T680 requires removal of the valve cover, inspection of the camshaft and valve train components, replacement of the defective camshaft or position sensor, repair of any damaged wiring or connectors, adjustment of valve lash, oil and filter change to remove debris, and final system calibration/reset.

title: Transmission Problem
problemDescription:
During the inspection of the transmission and its electronic control module (TCM/ECU), several problems were identified:
	1.	Electronic Module Corrosion and Damage
	•	Rust and moisture were found around the module’s mounting bolts, indicating water intrusion.
	•	A black burnt spot on the circuit board suggests possible overheating or a short circuit, which can cause intermittent electrical failures or loss of communication between the TCM and the transmission.
	2.	Internal Transmission Wear
	•	Inside the transmission housing there is a heavy reddish-brown dust, which is a mixture of burned oil and friction material from the clutch packs.
	•	This points to prolonged clutch wear and possible overheating, which can lead to slipping gears, harsh shifting, or hydraulic pressure loss.
	3.	Hydraulic Rail “B” Concerns
	•	The “rail B” is the hydraulic control assembly responsible for directing fluid pressure to the correct clutches during gear changes.
	•	If the electronic module fails to send accurate signals, or if contamination from friction material blocks the passages, the rail B cannot operate correctly—causing delayed or erratic shifting.
